Web search results for query: "vite ssr @popperjs/core commonjs named export placements astro 2024 2025"

Links: [{"title":"Build Options | Vite","url":"https://vite.dev/config/build-options"},{"title":"Common Issues | vite-plugin-ssr","url":"https://vite-plugin-ssr.com/common-issues"},{"title":"SSR: named imports from lodash · vitejs/vite · Discussion #16005","url":"https://github.com/vitejs/vite/discussions/16005"},{"title":"vite-ssr - npm","url":"https://www.npmjs.com/package/vite-ssr"},{"title":"Broken npm package | vite-plugin-ssr","url":"https://vite-plugin-ssr.com/broken-npm-package"},{"title":"Preparing SSR for General Availability: Problematic Dependencies and API Improvements · vitejs/vite · Discussion #4230","url":"https://github.com/vitejs/vite/discussions/4230"},{"title":"Understanding how Vite deals with your node_modules - DEV Community","url":"https://dev.to/jinjiang/understanding-how-vite-deals-with-your-nodemodules-3pdf"},{"title":"CJS named imports in an ESM library · Issue #14332 · vitejs/vite","url":"https://github.com/vitejs/vite/issues/14332"},{"title":"Module is a CommonJS module, which may not support all module.exports as named exports. · Issue #220 · intlify/bundle-tools","url":"https://github.com/intlify/bundle-tools/issues/220"},{"title":"pmtiles in SSR in sveltekit v2, vite 5, Astro (ES6 module problems) · Issue #317 · protomaps/PMTiles","url":"https://github.com/protomaps/PMTiles/issues/317"}]

Based on the search results, I found information about Vite SSR issues with CommonJS named exports, though there wasn't a specific result for `@popperjs/core` with the `placements` export in Astro. However, the search results provide relevant solutions for this type of issue.

## Summary of Findings

The search results show this is a common issue when using Vite SSR with CommonJS modules that don't properly support named exports. The error typically looks like:

`SyntaxError: Named export 'SomeImport' not found. The requested module 'some-library' is a CommonJS module, which may not support all module.exports as named exports.`

### Solutions

**1. Use `ssr.noExternal` configuration:**

The issue can be fixed by adding the problematic package to `ssr.noExternal` in your vite.config.ts:
```js
import { defineConfig } from 'vite'
export default defineConfig({
  ssr: {
    noExternal: ['pmtiles', 'maplibre-gl']
  }
})
```

For your case with `@popperjs/core`, you would add it to the `noExternal` array.

**2. Use `ssr.optimizeDeps.include` combined with `noExternal`:**

A more robust solution is to use both `ssr.optimizeDeps.include` and `ssr.noExternal`:
```js
export default defineConfig({
  ssr: {
    optimizeDeps: {
      include: ["lodash"]
    },
    noExternal: ['lodash', 'foo']
  }
})
```

**3. Change the import style (workaround):**

If the above doesn't work, you can try changing your import style:
```js
- import theDefaultExport from 'some-library'
+ import lib from 'some-library';
+ const theDefaultExport = lib.default ?? lib
```

### For Astro Specifically

In Astro, you would configure this in your `astro.config.mjs` under the Vite configuration:

```js
export default defineConfig({
  vite: {
    ssr: {
      noExternal: ['@popperjs/core']
    }
  }
})
```

Note that Vite purposely doesn't transpile server-side code but lets Node.js directly execute npm packages (to improve DX speed), but some packages contain code that needs to be added to `ssr.noExternal`.


